# loki-storage-finder

Find and download TSDB index and chunk files from any Loki storage backend (S3, GCS, Azure, filesystem).

Designed to be run locally, depends on the gloud specific auth mechanism - running ./setup-context in 
deployment tools is a good idea. Currently only tested against Loki running in Dev.


## Build

```
go build ./tools/loki-storage-finder/
```

## Usage

Generate a config template, then edit it with your storage details:

```
./loki-storage-finder --gen-config=gcs > config.yaml
```

It must contain the correct information to access the storage bucket used by Loki!

Next, identify the tenant_id in question from gcom - this example uses 29 which is the ID for dev.

This finds the index and chunk files for this tenant and time range:

```
./loki-storage-finder \
  --config.file=config.yaml \
  --tenant=29 \
  --start=2025-02-20T00:00:00Z \
  --end=2025-02-21T00:00:00Z
```

TAKE NOTE OF THE INDEX PREFIX, IS NEEDED FOR LATER!!


Download the files for local playback:

```
./loki-storage-finder \
  --config.file=config.yaml \
  --tenant=29 \
  --start=2025-02-20T00:00:00Z \
  --end=2025-02-21T00:00:00Z \
  --download /tmp/loki
```

Downloaded chunk files are automatically normalized (base64-encoded filenames, `:` delimiters) so a local Loki instance can read them directly. Use `--no-normalize-for-filesystem` to preserve the original cloud key format (may differ depending on the cloud provider).

## Local playback

First edit `loki-config.yaml` to specify the index prefix that you got above (it is used to name the index files, they are of this form `/tmp/loki/index/${PREFIX}_{NUMBER}`)

Run a local Loki instance against the downloaded files:

```
docker run --rm \
  --name loki \
  -p 3100:3100 \
  --mount type=bind,source="$PWD/loki-config.yaml",target="/etc/loki/local-config.yaml" \
  --mount type=bind,source="/tmp/loki",target="/loki/chunks" \
  grafana/loki:latest
```

Query with the matching tenant ID:

```
curl -s -H "X-Scope-OrgID: 29" 'http://localhost:3100/loki/api/v1/label' | jq .
```


